04952nam a22008295i 9780231511384DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2009    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315113847 a10.7312/finc139462doi  a(DE-B1597)458847  a(OCoLC)1013953039  a(OCoLC)979831921  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aGT497.M4bF56 2010 7aREL0930002bisacsh04a974.4/022221 aFinch, Martha, eauthor.10aDissenting Bodies :bCorporealities in Early New England /cMartha Finch. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource :b9 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Embodying Godliness -- t1. Massasoit's Stool and Wituwamat's Head: Body Encounters -- t2. A Banquet in the Wilderness: Bodies and the Environment -- t3. As on a Hill: Public Bodies -- t4. The True and Visible Church: The Body of Christ -- t5. As in a Mirror: Domestic Bodies -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor the Puritan separatists of seventeenth-century New England, "godliness," as manifested by the body, was the sign of election, and the body, with its material demands and metaphorical significance, became the axis upon which all colonial activity and religious meaning turned. Drawing on literature, documents, and critical studies of embodiment as practiced in the New England colonies, Martha L. Finch launches a fascinating investigation into the scientific, theological, and cultural conceptions of corporeality at a pivotal moment in Anglo-Protestant history. Not only were settlers forced to interact bodily with native populations and other "new world" communities, they also fought starvation and illness; were whipped, branded, hanged, and murdered; sang, prayed, and preached; engaged in sexual relations; and were baptized according to their faith. All these activities shaped the colonists' understanding of their existence and the godly principles of their young society. Finch focuses specifically on Plymouth Colony and those who endeavored to make visible what they believed to be God's divine will. Quakers, Indians, and others challenged these beliefs, and the constant struggle to survive, build cohesive communities, and regulate behavior forced further adjustments. Merging theological, medical, and other positions on corporeality with testimonies on colonial life, Finch brilliantly complicates our encounter with early Puritan New England.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aBritish AmericanszMassachusettsxHistoryy17th century. 0aCommunity lifezMassachusettsxHistoryy17th century. 0aHuman bodyxSocial aspectszMassachusettsxHistoryy17th century. 0aHuman bodyzMassachusettsxReligious aspectsxHistoryy17th century. 0aPilgrims (New Plymouth Colony)xSocial life and customs. 0aProtestantszMassachusettsxHistoryy17th century. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Calvinist.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066254208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045952440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/finc13946423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231511384.jpg  a978-3-11-044247-2  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013  a978-3-11-045952-4  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-066254-2  CUP eBook Package 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-d